        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Oct 15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I hope that you will excuse me troubling you, but I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. be <hi rend="underline">greatly</hi> obliged if you could send me pretty soon (as my M.S. must go to the Printers) any information on the Egyptian goose, <hi rend="underline">both sifting the</hi> <hi rend="underline">water &amp; biting or tearing like a common goose the herbage</hi>.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I hope that you received safely the P.O.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> &amp; the 2 geese which were returned.</p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8011.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Edward Bartlett, 16 October 1871</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7965.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Edward Bartlett, [24] September [1871]</ref>. CD refers to the sixth edition of <hi rend="italic">Origin.</hi> The Egyptian goose is now <hi rend="italic">Alopochen aegyptiaca.</hi></note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">P.O.: postal order. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7965.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Edward Bartlett, [24] September [1871]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
